merging dataset

# importing dataset
rpas <- read_excel("Norm145 Responses with Joint (Jessa Reviewed) and Individual R-PAS Codes.xlsx") %>% 
  rename(Filename = `FileName...1`,
         ID = `ID_Num...2`,
         Card = `Card_Num...3`,
         Rn = `Resp_Num...4`,
         FQ = `FQ...64`,
         R_incard = `R_InCard...5`)


data_rpas <- rpas %>% select(Filename, Card, Rn, FQ, R_incard) %>% 
  group_by(Filename, Card) %>% 
  mutate(Rn_card = 1:n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(FQ = case_when(FQ == "o" ~ 3,
                        FQ == "u" ~ 2,
                        FQ == "-" ~ 1,
                        FQ == "n" ~ 0,))

#cor.test(data_rpas$R_incard, data_rpas$Rn_card)

data <- data_rpas %>% 
  filter(Rn_card <= 4, FQ != 0) %>% 
  mutate(FQ2 = case_when(FQ == 3 ~ 3,
                         FQ == 2 ~ 3,
                         FQ == 1 ~ 1))
data

Analysis

Iâ€™ve created a new column in the dataset called Rn_card. After running this, Iâ€™ve realized that this dataset contained a column named R_incard which seems to be the same the new variable Rn_card. I decided keep both and work with Rn_card give the syntax was already organized to do that. This new variable indicates what is the number of response per card. The count reset in each card. Take a look in the data dataframe below, also this dataframe only contains Filename, Card, Rn, FQ, R_incard, and Rn_card, which are the only important variables for this analysis:

Main Analysis

So the idea was to test whether FQ get worse as the response number increase. For instance, first response to a card would have a better FQ than the second response, which will be better then the third response, which will be better than the four response.

As an extreme scenario we are testing if we have cases like this:

  • First response to a card -> FQo (3)
  • Second response to a card -> Fqu (2)
  • Third response to a card -> Fq- (1)
  • Fourth response to a card -> Fqn (0)

given FQo == 3, FQu ==2, FQ- == 1, FQn == 0, we anticipate a negative correlation between the number of the response per card with FQ.

This is the result from rpas dataset, we observed a correlation with r = -.16, p < .001 , 95%CI[-.19, -.12]. This result go in the same direction and roughly the same magnitude we found on Klineâ€™s dataset (r = -.13), and Giâ€™s dataset (r = -.09)

From the scatterplot above, is hard to tell how the association really looks like, because most of the dots are on top of the others, so below, we can see a new scatterplot, presenting the same information as above but dispersing the dots a bit so we can better see the really amount of dots in each quadrant. The shadowy area around the regression line shows the CI.

This way we can see that the association is indeed low. However, it is negative, which is in the expected direction.

After seeing the effect above, I got curious to see how would be these associations per card! In the graph below we can see the association between FQ per number of the response (Rn_card) per Card. Each graph represent the correlation in the specific Card. See below.

Being more precise, but still the same analysis per card, below we can see the strength of the association between FQ and Rn_card per card. In the y axis we see Pearsonâ€™s r. The error bars show CI. It seems that the biggest associations was found on Card V (r = -.33, p = .052, 95%CI [-.43, -.22]), followed by Card IV (r = -.32, p < .001, 95%CI [-.42, -.21]), and Card VII (r = -.30, p < .001, 95%CI [-.40, -.19]). But in general, cards III through VIII had roughly same magnitude. It is interesting to notice that Card V again presented one of the greatest magnitudes, which was the same for Klineâ€™s (r = -.33, p < .001, 95%CI [-.48, -.16]) and Giâ€™s (r = -.36, p < .001, 95%CI [-.53, -.17])dataset. The only unexpected result was the the sig. positive correlation on card IX. Which was also positive but not sig. in Giâ€™s dataset (but not on Klineâ€™s). From a qualitative point of view, Card IX is indeed the most unorganized card, that could justify that in a first impression, people canâ€™t see much thing, and rely more in inner experience to come up with a response, but after taking more time examining the card, they start coming up with more common perceptions. Which seems to be a different process than the process that occurs on other cards. In which people start seeing commom and well-fit percepts and go to more non-common and percepts that doesnâ€™t fit the blot. However, this result was not replicated in the Klineâ€™s dataset that showed correlation of r = -.25, p = .01, 95%[-.41, -.08].
